Social engineering tricks people into revealing confidential information or granting access by exploiting trust or emotions like fear or curiosity. Instead of hacking technology, attackers manipulate human behavior through fake emails, calls, or messages pretending to be someone trustworthy. Protecting yourself involves being cautious, verifying identities, and not sharing sensitive info easily. Learning about “phishing,” “pretexting,” and “impostor scams” can deepen understanding. Awareness of these tactics strengthens privacy and security, making it harder for attackers to bypass strong technical protections in secure messaging.